gaged in the everyday struggles that occur in deindustrialising settings under neoliberal neo-authoritarianism. The book suggests a novel approach to everyday life in post-industrial cities. Drawing on an ethnographic study with elements of arts-based research, the book presents a new genre of writing about workers influenced by the avant-garde documentary tradition and working-class literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCity and town lifezRussia (Federation)y21st century. 0aWorking classzRussia (Federation)xPolitical and social viewsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aPierre Bourdieu.  aRaymond Williams.  aauthoritarianism.  adeindustrialisation.  ainequality.  amaterialism.  aneoliberalism.  apostsocialism.  aurbanism.  aworking class.1 aVanke, Alexandrina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2024 eBook-Packagez9783111332345oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616764440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526167644423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526167644/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2024